00:37:25,368 --> 00:37:27,161
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

511
00:37:30,332 --> 00:37:33,834
So I'm going to give you a little
something you can't take off.

512
00:37:46,014 --> 00:37:49,683
You know, Lieutenant, you're
getting pretty good at that.

513
00:37:50,185 --> 00:37:53,354
You know how you get to
Carnegie Hall, don't you?

514
00:37:54,272 --> 00:37:55,522
Practise.

515
00:37:57,525 --> 00:37:59,526
Chapter Three

516
00:37:59,611 --> 00:38:03,405
GERMAN NIGHT IN PARIS

517
00:38:04,366 --> 00:38:06,659
1944

518
00:38:07,369 --> 00:38:09,703
JUNE

519
00:39:03,258 --> 00:39:04,258
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

520
00:39:04,384 --> 00:39:05,592
What starts tomorrow?

521
00:39:07,762 --> 00:39:09,388
A Max Linder festival.

522
00:39:11,391 --> 00:39:13,100
I always preferred
Linder to Chaplin.

523
00:39:14,602 --> 00:39:17,229
Except Linder never made a
film as good as "The Kid."

524
00:39:17,939 --> 00:39:20,274
The chase climax of
"The Kid," superb.

525
00:39:27,282 --> 00:39:28,615
I adore your cinema very much.

526
00:39:29,325 --> 00:39:30,409
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

527
00:39:30,493 --> 00:39:31,618
Merci.

528
00:39:31,953 --> 00:39:32,953
Is it yours?

529
00:39:34,664 --> 00:39:35,748
Do I own it?

530
00:39:35,832 --> 00:39:36,957
Yes.

531
00:39:37,459 --> 00:39:38,584
Yes.

532
00:39:40,962 --> 00:39:43,630
How is it a girl as young
as you owns a cinema?

533
00:39:44,132 --> 00:39:45,591
My aunt left it to me.

534
00:39:46,801 --> 00:39:48,677
Merci for hosting a German night.

535
00:39:50,096 --> 00:39:51,138
I don't have a choice...

536
00:39:51,806 --> 00:39:52,806
but you're welcome.

537
00:39:53,767 --> 00:39:55,768
I love the Riefenstahl
mountain films...

538
00:39:56,144 --> 00:39:57,144
especially Piz Palü.

539
00:39:58,480 --> 00:40:00,814
It's nice to see a French girl
who's an admirer of Riefenstahl.

540
00:40:01,441 --> 00:40:03,317
"Admire" would not really
be the word I would use...

541
00:40:03,610 --> 00:40:06,278
to describe my feelings
towards Fräulein Riefenstahl.

542
00:40:08,490 --> 00:40:10,491
But you do admire the
director Pabst, don't you?

543
00:40:12,452 --> 00:40:14,119
That's why you include his
name on the marquee...

544
00:40:15,121 --> 00:40:16,205
when you didn't have to.

545
00:40:24,047 --> 00:40:28,383
I'm French. We respect
directors in our country.

546
00:40:29,219 --> 00:40:30,385
Even Germans.

547
00:40:30,678 --> 00:40:31,845
Even Germans, yes.

548
00:40:33,181 --> 00:40:34,848
Merci for your assistance,
soldier. Adieu.

549
00:40:37,018 --> 00:40:38,060
You're not finished.

550
00:40:38,686 --> 00:40:39,853
I'll finish in the morning.

551
00:40:40,146 --> 00:40:41,355
May I ask your name?

552
00:40:44,192 --> 00:40:45,192
You wish to see my papers?

553
00:41:00,375 --> 00:41:01,375
Emmanuelle Mimieux.

554
00:41:02,877 --> 00:41:04,169
That's a very pretty name.

555
00:41:05,380 --> 00:41:06,380
Merci.

556
00:41:06,548 --> 00:41:07,756
Are you finished with my papers?

557
00:41:12,053 --> 00:41:13,762
Mademoiselle, may I
introduce myself...

558
00:41:14,722 --> 00:41:15,931
Fredrick Zoller.

559
00:41:23,439 --> 00:41:24,523
Well...

560
00:41:25,859 --> 00:41:29,736
it's been a pleasure chatting
with a fellow cinema lover.

561
00:41:31,114 --> 00:41:32,197
Sweet dreams, mademoiselle.

562
00:41:33,032 --> 00:41:34,074
Adieu.

563
00:42:14,616 --> 00:42:15,657
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

564
00:42:15,783 --> 00:42:16,825
Hello, mademoiselle.

565
00:42:17,243 --> 00:42:18,285
May I join you?

566
00:42:19,579 --> 00:42:20,621
Look, Fredrick...

567
00:42:22,123 --> 00:42:23,123
You remember my name?

568
00:42:23,458 --> 00:42:24,458
Yes.

569
00:42:25,627 --> 00:42:28,295
Look, you seem a pleasant
enough fellow...

570
00:42:28,421 --> 00:42:29,463
Thank you.

571
00:42:29,672 --> 00:42:30,756
You're welcome.

572
00:42:31,299 --> 00:42:32,841
Regardless, I want you
to stop pestering me.

573
00:42:36,429 --> 00:42:38,138
I apologise, mademoiselle...

574
00:42:38,806 --> 00:42:40,015
I wasn't trying to be a pest.

575
00:42:41,142 --> 00:42:42,643
I was simply trying
to be friendly.

576
00:42:43,770 --> 00:42:44,853
I don't wish to be your friend.

577
00:42:46,439 --> 00:42:47,481
Why not?

578
00:42:49,525 --> 00:42:50,984
Don't act like an
infant. You know why.

579
00:42:53,655 --> 00:42:55,155
I'm more than just a uniform.

580
00:42:55,615 --> 00:42:56,657
Not to me.

581
00:42:57,325 --> 00:42:59,451
If you are so desperate for
a French girlfriend...

582
00:43:00,203 --> 00:43:01,620
I suggest you try Vichy.

583
00:43:03,498 --> 00:43:04,998
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

584
00:43:05,124 --> 00:43:08,418
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

585
00:43:33,152 --> 00:43:34,236
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

586
00:43:34,362 --> 00:43:35,404
Who are you?

587
00:43:35,905 --> 00:43:37,155
I thought I was just a uniform.

588
00:43:37,907 --> 00:43:39,408
You're not just a German soldier.

589
00:43:41,035 --> 00:43:42,077
Are you somebody's son?

590
00:43:42,912 --> 00:43:45,038
Most German soldiers
are somebody's son.

591
00:43:49,043 --> 00:43:50,711
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

592
00:43:53,047 --> 00:43:54,214
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

593
00:44:17,071 --> 00:44:18,238
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

594
00:44:18,323 --> 00:44:20,657
You're a very lucky girl,
catching a brave war hero.

595
00:44:20,825 --> 00:44:23,577
No, no, no, no, the mademoiselle
is not my girlfriend.

596
00:44:24,746 --> 00:44:27,247
Can you write "Amour Babette"?

597
00:44:29,667 --> 00:44:31,418
(BOTH SPEAKING GERMAN)

598
00:44:35,882 --> 00:44:37,007
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

599
00:44:47,769 --> 00:44:48,852
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

600
00:44:48,936 --> 00:44:50,103
So you're a war hero.

601
00:44:51,606 --> 00:44:52,689
What did you do?

602
00:44:56,736 --> 00:44:57,778
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

603
00:44:57,904 --> 00:44:59,613
I was alone in a bell tower
in a walled off city.

604
00:45:00,531 --> 00:45:01,963
It was myself and
a thousand rounds

605
00:45:01,964 --> 00:45:03,116
of ammo, in a bird's nest...

606
00:45:04,410 --> 00:45:06,286
against three hundred
enemy soldiers.

607
00:45:07,789 --> 00:45:08,955
What's a bird's nest?

608
00:45:11,751 --> 00:45:14,795
A bird's nest is what a sniper
would call a bell tower.

609
00:45:15,296 --> 00:45:16,672
It's a high structure, offering a

610
00:45:16,673 --> 00:45:18,256
three hundred and
sixty degree view.

611
00:45:19,217 --> 00:45:21,218
Very advantageous for marksmen.

612
00:45:23,388 --> 00:45:24,638
How many did you kill?

613
00:45:26,307 --> 00:45:27,432
Sixty-eight.

614
00:45:29,644 --> 00:45:30,769
The first day.

615
00:45:33,106 --> 00:45:34,314
A hundred and fifty...

616
00:45:36,275 --> 00:45:37,317
the second day.

617
00:45:40,154 --> 00:45:41,655
Thirty-two the third day.

618
00:45:44,242 --> 00:45:46,076
On the fourth day
they exited the city.

619
00:45:48,329 --> 00:45:51,748
Naturally, my war story received
a lot of attention in Germany...

620
00:45:52,125 --> 00:45:53,667
that's why they all recognise me.

621
00:45:55,002 --> 00:45:57,337
They call me the
German Sergeant York.

622
00:45:58,673 --> 00:46:00,257
Maybe they'll make a film
about your exploits.

623
00:46:02,802 --> 00:46:05,345
Well, that's just what
Joseph Goebbels thought.

624
00:46:06,180 --> 00:46:08,682
So he did and called
it "Nation's Pride."

625
00:46:10,017 --> 00:46:14,438
And they wanted me
to play myself...

626
00:46:15,773 --> 00:46:16,815
so I did.

627
00:46:17,358 --> 00:46:19,818
Joseph thinks this movie will be
proven to be his masterpiece.

628
00:46:20,486 --> 00:46:22,154
And I will be the
German Van Johnson.

629
00:46:23,030 --> 00:46:24,489
"Nation's Pride" is about you?

630
00:46:26,659 --> 00:46:28,702
"Nation's Pride" is starring you?

631
00:46:28,870 --> 00:46:29,953
I know.

632
00:46:30,204 --> 00:46:31,204
Comical?

633
00:46:32,039 --> 00:46:33,707
Well, good luck with
your movie, Private. I

634
00:46:33,708 --> 00:46:35,375
hope all goes well for
Joseph and yourself.

635
00:46:37,378 --> 00:46:38,879
(SAYING GOODBYE IN FRENCH)

636
00:46:45,219 --> 00:46:46,386
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

637
00:46:46,471 --> 00:46:47,512
Goodbye.

638
00:46:49,348 --> 00:46:50,807
- Do you need help?
- No, it's okay.

639
00:46:51,392 --> 00:46:52,826
If you need me, I'll be
in the storage room.

640
00:46:52,827 --> 00:46:53,869
Okay, my love.

641
00:47:26,385 --> 00:47:27,427
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

642
00:47:27,553 --> 00:47:28,637
Mademoiselle Mimieux?

643
00:47:30,932 --> 00:47:31,973
Yes?

644
00:47:32,975 --> 00:47:34,935
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

645
00:47:35,770 --> 00:47:36,811
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

646
00:47:36,938 --> 00:47:38,021
Is this your cinema?

647
00:47:38,105 --> 00:47:39,147
Yes.

648
00:47:40,316 --> 00:47:42,150
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

649
00:47:42,276 --> 00:47:43,360
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

650
00:47:43,444 --> 00:47:44,486
Come down.

651
00:47:47,240 --> 00:47:48,281
Please.

652
00:48:04,799 --> 00:48:06,033
I don't understand.
What have I done?

653
00:48:06,092 --> 00:48:07,133
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

654
00:48:07,260 --> 00:48:08,394
She wants to know what she's done.

655
00:48:08,469 --> 00:48:09,844
Get your ass in that car.

656
00:48:29,156 --> 00:48:30,156
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

657
00:48:30,283 --> 00:48:32,803
It's only the offspring
of slaves that allows

658
00:48:32,804 --> 00:48:34,995
America to be competitive
athletically.

659
00:48:35,997 --> 00:48:40,292
American Olympic gold can
be measured in Negro sweat.

660
00:48:54,640 --> 00:48:55,724
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

661
00:48:55,850 --> 00:48:57,017
Good, you came.

662
00:48:57,143 --> 00:48:59,227
I wasn't sure whether or not
you'd accept my invitation.

663
00:49:00,062 --> 00:49:01,062
Invitation?

664
00:49:01,063 --> 00:49:02,063
(GOEBBELS SPEAKING GERMAN)

665
00:49:02,064 --> 00:49:03,531
Is that the young lady
in question, Fredrick?

666
00:49:03,532 --> 00:49:04,532
Yes, it is, Dr Goebbels.

667
00:49:04,692 --> 00:49:05,692
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

668
00:49:05,860 --> 00:49:07,460
Emmanuelle, there is
somebody I want you to meet.

669
00:49:09,697 --> 00:49:11,914
Emmanuelle Mimieux,
I'd like to introduce

670
00:49:11,915 --> 00:49:13,867
you to the minister
of propaganda...

671
00:49:14,535 --> 00:49:17,203
the leader of the entire
German film industry...

672
00:49:17,705 --> 00:49:21,541
and now that I'm an actor,
my boss, Dr Joseph Goebbels.

673
00:49:21,917 --> 00:49:23,043
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

674
00:49:23,169 --> 00:49:24,703
Your reputation precedes
you, Fräulein Mimieux.

675
00:49:30,718 --> 00:49:31,760
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

676
00:49:31,886 --> 00:49:34,220
And normally, this is Herr
Goebbels' French interpreter...

677
00:49:34,555 --> 00:49:35,764
Mademoiselle Francesca Mondino.

678
00:49:36,182 --> 00:49:37,223
Hello.

679
00:49:41,937 --> 00:49:42,979
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

680
00:49:43,064 --> 00:49:44,105
Hello.

681
00:49:45,900 --> 00:49:47,859
And you've met the Major.

682
00:49:48,110 --> 00:49:49,194
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

683
00:49:49,278 --> 00:49:50,479
Actually, I didn't
introduce myself.

684
00:49:50,480 --> 00:49:51,745
Major Dieter Hellstrom
of the Gestapo.

685
00:49:52,239 --> 00:49:53,406
At your service, mademoiselle.

686
00:49:54,408 --> 00:49:55,450
Please allow me...

687
00:49:56,744 --> 00:49:57,786
have a seat, please.

688
00:50:04,293 --> 00:50:06,920
Try the champagne,
mademoiselle, it's quite good.

689
00:50:14,720 --> 00:50:15,762
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

690
00:50:15,888 --> 00:50:18,056
I must say, Fräulein, I should
be rather annoyed with you.

691
00:50:18,140 --> 00:50:19,265
(TRANSLATING IN FRENCH)

692
00:50:20,601 --> 00:50:22,060
I arrive in France...

693
00:50:22,144 --> 00:50:24,145
and I wish to have
lunch with my star.

694
00:50:24,271 --> 00:50:25,438
(TRANSLATING IN FRENCH)

695
00:50:26,273 --> 00:50:27,273
Little do I know...

696
00:50:27,942 --> 00:50:30,276
he's become the toast of Paris.

697
00:50:30,569 --> 00:50:32,445
And now he must find time for me.

698
00:50:32,571 --> 00:50:34,948
(TRANSLATING IN FRENCH)

699
00:50:37,326 --> 00:50:41,955
People wait in line
hours, days to see me.

700
00:50:42,957 --> 00:50:45,125
For the Führer...

701
00:50:46,252 --> 00:50:48,461
and Private Zoller, I wait.

702
00:50:49,630 --> 00:50:53,174
So finally, I'm granted an
audience with the young Private.

703
00:50:53,300 --> 00:50:54,342
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING FRENCH)

704
00:50:56,512 --> 00:50:59,973
And he spends the entire lunch
speaking of you and your cinema.

705
00:51:00,808 --> 00:51:02,375
So Fräulein Mimieux, let's
get down to business.

706
00:51:02,376 --> 00:51:03,384
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

707
00:51:03,410 --> 00:51:04,544
Herr Minister Doctor Goebbels...

708
00:51:04,545 --> 00:51:05,620
I haven't informed her yet.

709
00:51:05,646 --> 00:51:07,981
Unless the girl's a simpleton, I'm
sure she's figured it out by now.

710
00:51:08,315 --> 00:51:09,816
After all, she does
operate a cinema.

711
00:51:10,985 --> 00:51:12,026
Francesca, tell her.

712
00:51:12,153 --> 00:51:13,194
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

713
00:51:13,320 --> 00:51:15,487
What they are trying to tell you,
Emmanuelle, is Private Zoller...

714
00:51:15,489 --> 00:51:16,882
has spent the last
hour at lunch trying

715
00:51:16,883 --> 00:51:18,032
to convince Monsieur Goebbels...

716
00:51:18,159 --> 00:51:20,660
to abandon previous plans for
Private Zoller's film premiere...

717
00:51:21,162 --> 00:51:23,663
and change the venue
to your cinema.

718
00:51:24,957 --> 00:51:25,957
What?

719
00:51:26,041 --> 00:51:27,125
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

720
00:51:27,209 --> 00:51:28,251
I wanted to inform her.

721
00:51:28,335 --> 00:51:30,462
Shit. I apologise, Private,
of course you did.

722
00:51:30,546 --> 00:51:31,671
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

723
00:51:31,756 --> 00:51:32,839
What's the issue?

724
00:51:33,174 --> 00:51:36,009
The Private wanted to inform
the mademoiselle himself.

725
00:51:36,385 --> 00:51:37,510
Nonsense.

726
00:51:38,512 --> 00:51:40,847
Until I ask my questions,
he has nothing to inform.

727
00:51:41,599 --> 00:51:43,378
Let the record state,
I have not agreed

728
00:51:43,379 --> 00:51:44,934
to switch cinemas for my premiere.

729
00:51:45,770 --> 00:51:46,936
Duly noted.

730
00:51:51,942 --> 00:51:53,526
You have opera boxes?

731
00:51:53,611 --> 00:51:54,694
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING FRENCH)

732
00:51:55,112 --> 00:51:56,196
Yes.

733
00:51:57,198 --> 00:51:58,239
How many?

734
00:52:00,034 --> 00:52:01,075
Two.

735
00:52:01,202 --> 00:52:02,410
(TRANSLATES IN GERMAN)

736
00:52:02,620 --> 00:52:04,245
More would be better.

737
00:52:04,371 --> 00:52:05,455
(GOEBBELS SPEAKING GERMAN)

738
00:52:05,539 --> 00:52:07,123
How many seats in your auditorium?

739
00:52:07,750 --> 00:52:08,833
Three hundred and fifty.

740
00:52:08,918 --> 00:52:10,502
(TRANSLATING IN GERMAN)

741
00:52:12,546 --> 00:52:15,882
That's almost four hundred
less than The Ritz.

742
00:52:16,133 --> 00:52:17,550
But Dr Goebbels...

743
00:52:18,052 --> 00:52:19,252
that's not such a terrible thing.

744
00:52:19,887 --> 00:52:21,485
You said yourself you
didn't want to indulge

745
00:52:21,486 --> 00:52:22,764
every two-faced
French bourgeois...

746
00:52:22,890 --> 00:52:24,090
taking up space, currying favour.

747
00:52:24,558 --> 00:52:27,101
With less seats, it makes
the event more exclusive.

748
00:52:27,978 --> 00:52:30,980
You're not trying to fill the
house, they're fighting for seats.

749
00:52:31,899 --> 00:52:33,316
Besides, to hell with the French.

750
00:52:33,776 --> 00:52:37,237
This is a German night, a German
event, a German celebration.

751
00:52:38,155 --> 00:52:40,281
This night is for you, me...

752
00:52:40,908 --> 00:52:42,784
for the German military,
the high command...

753
00:52:42,910 --> 00:52:43,910
their family and friends.

754
00:52:44,578 --> 00:52:46,287
The only people who should
be allowed in the room...

755
00:52:46,413 --> 00:52:48,748
are people who will be moved
by the exploits on the screen.

756
00:52:58,259 --> 00:53:00,260
I see your public
speaking has improved.

757
00:53:01,679 --> 00:53:03,763
It appears I've created a monster.

758
00:53:06,934 --> 00:53:09,269
A strangely persuasive monster.

759
00:53:15,442 --> 00:53:18,152
When the war is over,
politics await.

760
00:53:26,620 --> 00:53:27,954
Well, Private...

761
00:53:31,458 --> 00:53:33,835
though it is true, I'm inclined
to indulge you anything...

762
00:53:34,795 --> 00:53:36,860
I must watch a film
in this young lady's

763
00:53:36,861 --> 00:53:38,673
cinema before I can
say, yes or no.

764
00:53:40,676 --> 00:53:42,639
So young lady, you
are to close your

765
00:53:42,640 --> 00:53:44,762
cinema for a private
screening tonight.

766
00:53:44,847 --> 00:53:46,180
(TRANSLATING IN FRENCH)

767
00:53:50,144 --> 00:53:52,979
What German films do you have?

768
00:53:53,522 --> 00:53:54,981
Ah, Landa, you are here.

769
00:53:58,152 --> 00:53:59,277
(FREDRICK SPEAKING FRENCH)

